<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="374" type="reference_group">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,402,823]" pageId="7" pageNumber="374">
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Pourtales" baseAuthorityYear="1867" box="[151,375,402,427]" class="Anthozoa" family="Aphanipathidae" genus="Distichopathes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Antipatharia" pageId="7" pageNumber="374" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="filix">
<emphasis box="[151,375,402,427]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="374">Distichopathes filix</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
forms very sparsely-branched colonies that are branched in a single plane (
<figureCitation box="[1278,1424,402,427]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1895,1917]" captionTargetBox="[151,1426,878,1874]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[151,1436,878,1874]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 5. Distichopathes filix from Bermuda showing (a) colonies in situ, (b) preserved specimen (scale bar = 4 cm), (c) polyps on basal part of pinnules under light microscopy (scale bar = 2 mm), (d) skeletal spines on a primary pinnule under SEM (scale bar = 200 µm), and (e) close-up of polypar spine under SEM (scale bar = 50 µm)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1042998/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="374">Figure 5a–b</figureCitation>
). Pinnulation is bilateral, and the pinnules in each lateral row alternate with those of the opposite row (
<figureCitation box="[1283,1424,438,463]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1895,1917]" captionTargetBox="[151,1426,878,1874]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[151,1436,878,1874]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 5. Distichopathes filix from Bermuda showing (a) colonies in situ, (b) preserved specimen (scale bar = 4 cm), (c) polyps on basal part of pinnules under light microscopy (scale bar = 2 mm), (d) skeletal spines on a primary pinnule under SEM (scale bar = 200 µm), and (e) close-up of polypar spine under SEM (scale bar = 50 µm)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1042998/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="374">Figure 5b–c</figureCitation>
). Spines are needle-shaped and covered with distinct tubercles on the distal third of their surface (
<figureCitation box="[1240,1381,474,499]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1895,1917]" captionTargetBox="[151,1426,878,1874]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[151,1436,878,1874]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 5. Distichopathes filix from Bermuda showing (a) colonies in situ, (b) preserved specimen (scale bar = 4 cm), (c) polyps on basal part of pinnules under light microscopy (scale bar = 2 mm), (d) skeletal spines on a primary pinnule under SEM (scale bar = 200 µm), and (e) close-up of polypar spine under SEM (scale bar = 50 µm)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1042998/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="374">Figure 5d–e</figureCitation>
). On the side of the corallum opposite to the one bearing the polyps, the spines are uniform in height and typically range between 90–120 µm (
<figureCitation box="[393,506,546,571]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1895,1917]" captionTargetBox="[151,1426,878,1874]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[151,1436,878,1874]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 5. Distichopathes filix from Bermuda showing (a) colonies in situ, (b) preserved specimen (scale bar = 4 cm), (c) polyps on basal part of pinnules under light microscopy (scale bar = 2 mm), (d) skeletal spines on a primary pinnule under SEM (scale bar = 200 µm), and (e) close-up of polypar spine under SEM (scale bar = 50 µm)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1042998/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="374">Figure 5d</figureCitation>
). In contrast, the side of the corallum bearing the polyps contains skeletal spines of greatly varying heights (
<figureCitation box="[425,540,582,607]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1895,1917]" captionTargetBox="[151,1426,878,1874]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[151,1436,878,1874]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 5. Distichopathes filix from Bermuda showing (a) colonies in situ, (b) preserved specimen (scale bar = 4 cm), (c) polyps on basal part of pinnules under light microscopy (scale bar = 2 mm), (d) skeletal spines on a primary pinnule under SEM (scale bar = 200 µm), and (e) close-up of polypar spine under SEM (scale bar = 50 µm)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1042998/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="374">Figure 5d</figureCitation>
). The tallest spines are located in the area underneath the outer edges of polyps and reach heights of 200–250 µm, whereas the shortest spines are situated in the area underneath the oral cone, and typically reach heights of only 200 µm (
<figureCitation box="[598,711,654,679]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1895,1917]" captionTargetBox="[151,1426,878,1874]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[151,1436,878,1874]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 5. Distichopathes filix from Bermuda showing (a) colonies in situ, (b) preserved specimen (scale bar = 4 cm), (c) polyps on basal part of pinnules under light microscopy (scale bar = 2 mm), (d) skeletal spines on a primary pinnule under SEM (scale bar = 200 µm), and (e) close-up of polypar spine under SEM (scale bar = 50 µm)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1042998/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="374">Figure 5d</figureCitation>
). Polyps are 0.7–1.0 mm in transverse diameter, and spaced 
<quantity metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.15" metricValueMax="1.2" metricValueMin="1.1" pageId="7" pageNumber="374" unit="mm" value="1.15" valueMax="1.2" valueMin="1.1">1.1– 1.2 mm</quantity>
apart (
<figureCitation box="[321,434,690,715]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1895,1917]" captionTargetBox="[151,1426,878,1874]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[151,1436,878,1874]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 5. Distichopathes filix from Bermuda showing (a) colonies in situ, (b) preserved specimen (scale bar = 4 cm), (c) polyps on basal part of pinnules under light microscopy (scale bar = 2 mm), (d) skeletal spines on a primary pinnule under SEM (scale bar = 200 µm), and (e) close-up of polypar spine under SEM (scale bar = 50 µm)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1042998/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="374">Figure 5c</figureCitation>
). The color of living colonies is bright yellow (
<figureCitation box="[984,1097,690,715]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1895,1917]" captionTargetBox="[151,1426,878,1874]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[151,1436,878,1874]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 5. Distichopathes filix from Bermuda showing (a) colonies in situ, (b) preserved specimen (scale bar = 4 cm), (c) polyps on basal part of pinnules under light microscopy (scale bar = 2 mm), (d) skeletal spines on a primary pinnule under SEM (scale bar = 200 µm), and (e) close-up of polypar spine under SEM (scale bar = 50 µm)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1042998/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="374">Figure 5a</figureCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Pourtales" baseAuthorityYear="1867" box="[1120,1200,690,715]" class="Anthozoa" family="Aphanipathidae" genus="Distichopathes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Antipatharia" pageId="7" pageNumber="374" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="filix">
<emphasis box="[1120,1200,690,715]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="374">D. filix</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has previously been reported from the Caribbean Sea and the Gulf of 
<collectingRegion box="[722,807,726,751]" country="Mexico" name="Mexico" pageId="7" pageNumber="374">
<collectingCountry box="[722,807,726,751]" name="Mexico" pageId="7" pageNumber="374">Mexico</collectingCountry>
</collectingRegion>
at depths ranging between 
<quantity box="[1127,1242,726,751]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.7299999999999995" metricValueMax="6.95" metricValueMin="0.51" pageId="7" pageNumber="374" unit="m" value="373.0" valueMax="695.0" valueMin="51.0">51–695 m</quantity>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Opresko" box="[1259,1431,726,751]" pageId="7" pageNumber="374" refString="Opresko, D. M. (2009) Antipatharia (Cnidaria) of the Gulf of Mexico. In: Tunnell, J. W. Jr., Felder, D. L. &amp; Earle, S. A. (Eds.), Gulf of Mexico origin, waters, and biota. Vol. 1. Biodiversity. Texas A &amp; M University Press, Corpus Christi, 359 - 363." type="book chapter" year="2009">Opresko, 2009</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Cairns" box="[151,360,762,787]" pageId="7" pageNumber="374" refString="Cairns, S. D., Opresko, D. M. &amp; Hopkins, T. S. (1993) New records of deep-water Cnidaria (Scleractinia &amp; Antipatharia) from the Gulf of Mexico. Northeast Gulf Science, 13, 1 - 11." type="journal article" year="1993">
Cairns 
<emphasis box="[231,287,762,787]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="374">et al.</emphasis>
, 1993
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Opresko" box="[372,539,762,787]" pageId="7" pageNumber="374" refString="Opresko, D. M. (1972) Redescriptions and reevaluations of the antipatharians described by L. F. de Pourtales. Bulletin of Marine Science, 22, 950 - 1017." type="journal article" year="1972">Opresko, 1972</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Brook" box="[551,694,762,787]" pageId="7" pageNumber="374" refString="Brook, G. (1889) Report on the Antipatharia. Report of the scientific results of the voyage of the H. M. S. Challenger. Zoology, 32, 1 - 222." type="journal article" year="1889">Brook, 1889</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Pourtales" box="[706,884,762,787]" pageId="7" pageNumber="374" refString="Pourtales, L. F. de (1871) Deep-sea corals. Illustrated catalogue of the museum of comparative zoology at Harvard College, 4, 52 - 55." type="journal article" year="1871">Pourtales, 1871</bibRefCitation>
). The only Bermudan specimen examined as part of this study was collected at a depth of 
<quantity box="[601,672,799,823]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.04" pageId="7" pageNumber="374" unit="m" value="304.0">304 m</quantity>
(
<tableCitation box="[686,770,798,823]" captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,239,440,463]" captionText="TABLE 1. Black coral specimens examined as part of this study (BAMZ = Bermuda Aquarium, Museum and Zoo; NR = not reported; * = new record for Bermuda)." pageId="7" pageNumber="374">Table 1</tableCitation>
).
</paragraph>
